Climbing across the USA

Just for fun, I wanted to create a way to visualize how climbing varies across the USA. Even though the initial product will be limited to CA+NH, understanding the landscape of climbing across the country would eventually be imporant for thinking about the challenges that might arise in scaling this project.

Characterize different climbing areas

The structure of mountain project is based on a nested hierarchy of areas (e.g. a state is an area, a park is a subarea within the state, individual mountains are subareas within parks, and individual walls are subareas within mountains. However, the user generally thinks about climbing destinations at the level of "park" or large scale "main" area. I therefore focus many of my analyses on "mainareas", operationalized as any area which is a direct descendant of a US state. I plot the number of climbs and areas by region to get a sense of how climbs are distributed across the country.

Initial Feature Selection: What kind of text is unique to rock climbing comments and descriptions?

There are a number of strongly valence words that might predict ratings, but in a very general way. These words might have very little to do with climbing, and provide little information when it comes to personalized recommendations (e.g. moving beyond overall popularity). To identify an initial space of climbing-specific features, I pull a non-climbing corpora of rating-associated text from Rotten Tomatoes. So I will have a set of text reviews related and not related to climbing.

In []: 
freqdf=mdf.maketextcomparedf(cdf)
In [485]: 
from nltk.tokenize import wordpunct_tokenize
from nltk.stem import WordNetLemmatizer as stemmer
from sklearn.feature_extraction.text import TfidfVectorizer
stemmer=stemmer()

for each climb, combined comments and descriptions into single text blob, and used CountVectorizer to compute the frequency of each text feature in the blob. I will also normalize this value by the length of the text (see Notebook 3) to generate a single score (proportion of blob word count that is the feature) for each text feature for each climb.

In [489]: 
#prep text
tokens=[word_tokenize(s) for s in freqdf['string'].values]
stemmedstrings=[' '.join([stemmer.lemmatize(w) for w in row]) for row in tokens]
In [490]: 
tfidf=TfidfVectorizer(stop_words='english')
tfidfmatrix=tfidf.fit_transform(stemmedstrings)
mat=tfidfmatrix.toarray()

computed tf-idf for each review/text blob and averaged the tf-idf scores within climbing and non-climbing text. then, subtracted the non-climbing averages from the climbing tf-idf averages and selected the 500 words that had the highest difference score. these are the top "climbing-specific" text features.

In [585]:

keepercolumns=[c for c in xdf.columns if c not in exclcols]
xdf=xdf[keepercolumns]

def gettop(diffs, allterms, topn=300):
    selected=diffs.iloc[:topn].index.values
    return list(selected)
